Cache.0001.description:
Your application is using a data cache.

Some caching solutions will only work on the local machine or within an on-premises network. Make sure that the cache your app is working with is available from Azure.

Use the link below to learn how caching solutions could be implemented in Azure.
Cache.0001.label: Data caching is detected

Database.0003.description:
System.Data.SqlClient dependency is detected.

While System.Data.SqlClient will work in Azure, the newer Microsoft.Data.SqlClient package is the primary .NET SQL client moving forward and receiving the latest features. For example, Microsoft.Data.SqlClient easily allows use of Azure Managed Identity from a connection string.
Database.0003.label: System.Data.SqlClient dependency detected

HTTP.0001.description:
Your application is trying to reach external resources via HTTP protocol.

Ensure the resources it is trying to reach are accessible from the Azure environment. If those HTTP requests are sent to internal services or services hosted on-prem, you probably will need to migrate those services to Azure as well.

Also, keep in mind that Azure App Service supports port 80 for HTTP and port 443 for HTTPS traffic. If you are using any other ports, you need to update them before moving to Azure.
HTTP.0001.label: Access to external resources via HTTP is detected

Identity.0002.description:
Your app is using windows authentication which is not supported on Azure App Service, Azure Container Apps and Azure Kubernetes Service.

Azure App Service provides built-in authentication and authorization capabilities, so you can sign in users and access data by writing minimal or no code in your web app.

Follow the link below for more information."
Identity.0002.label: Windows authentication detected

Local.0001.description:
Windows local system features usage detected.

Windows features like registry access, starting processes via shell, access to COM objects, using standard OS dialogs etc, will be restricted on Azure App Service. This indicates that your application might be broken in App Service sandbox environment or not scale well.

If you choose to use containerized Azure hosting options with Windows container, such as Azure AppService sandbox for Windows container, Azure Container Apps (ACA) or Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS), some scenarios might work, however scaling still might be an issue.

Recommendations:
    1. Avoid using Windows registry or default Windows UI elements and dialogs.
    2. If your application needs to read app-specific configuration, you can use the App Settings feature of Azure App Service, which allows you to store key-value pairs of configuration data for your application. You can access these settings from your code using environment variables. Another option is to use Azure App Configuration and Azure Key Vault to share application settings in a cloud-native way.
    3. If your application is writing data (like machine-wide settings cache), use an external data store like Azure SQL DB or Azure Cache for Redis.
    4. Instead of starting local worker processes use Azure Functions.
Local.0001.label: Windows local system features usage detected

links.title: App Service sandbox for Windows Container Web Apps

Local.0003.description:
Your application has local or network IO operations.

IO operations outside of the application folder might not be available on Azure App Service. Review and ensure IO APIs are attempting to access paths that will be available when your app is running on App Service sandbox. If you choose the containerized hosting option, your scenario still might be broken or have scalability issues.

Possible solutions:
    1. Files that the application needs can be deployed with the application or put in Azure Storage. You can use Azure Storage File Shares as a drop-in replacement for on-premises file share.
    2. Other services that the application depends on might need to be migrated to Azure, this way you will get the benefit of lower latency in the cloud.
    3. If your application needs to depend on services that run on-premise, you can connect your Azure and local networks with ExpressRoute, Hybrid Connections, or VPN solutions.
Local.0003.label: Local or network IO operations detected

Local.0007.description:
Local OS environment access detected.

When running in Azure App Service environment, your application can read environment variables that you define in App Service settings. Using environment API other than reading environment variables might indicate that your application depends on some local machine’s features and might be broken on App Service sandbox or not scale well. Review your scenarios and either refactor them to be more cloud friendly or choose the option in App Service to host your application in the sandbox for Windows Container Web Apps.

If you choose to use other Azure hosting options such as Azure Container Apps (ACA) or Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS), environment APIs might work, however scaling still might be an issue.
Local.0007.label: Local OS environment access detected

links.title: App Service sandbox for Windows Container Web Apps

Local.0012.description:
Local process start detected.

While it is possible to launch new worker processes in either Azure App Service or Azure Kubernetes Service environments, it is an anti-pattern to do so. Both expect to have a single process running and launching others can make it difficult to manage and debug the applications. Expecting another process or service to already be running in parallel with the service will not work in Azure App Service and is an anti-pattern in Kubernetes.
Local.0012.label: Local process start detected

Local.0021.description:
Dynamic assembly loading has been detected.

Make sure the loaded assembly is accessible in the cloud environment.

Note that incidents are not detected in dynamically loaded assemblies.
Local.0021.label: Detected loading of dynamic assemblies.

Perf.0001.description:
Synchronous API usage detected.

Using synchronous APIs can lead to more performance issues in Azure compared to on-premises environments due to different latency profiles. Consider adopting asynchronous code patterns.

In heavily loaded systems, especially where the I/O is substantial, using asynchronous patterns can improve overall throughput and performance. Asynchronous APIs enable a small pool of threads to manage thousands of concurrent requests without waiting on blocking calls. Instead of waiting for a long-running synchronous task to finish, the thread can handle another request. Conversely, numerous synchronous blocking calls can cause thread pool starvation and degrade response times.

Refer to the links below to learn more about asynchronous programming.
Perf.0001.label: Synchronous API usage detected

links.title: ASP.NET Core Best Practices: avoid blocking calls

Scale.0001.description:
Static content detected.

Your current approach of serving static content directly might lead to increased costs, performance issues, maintenance challenges (requiring application redeployment for content changes), and security risks.

Consider moving static content to Azure Blob Storage and adding Azure CDN.
Scale.0001.label: Static content detected

Scale.0003.description:
MachineKey dependency is detected.

MachineKey is used in ASP.NET apps to protect (encode) or unprotect (decode) data. It will work in Azure environments however it will impact scalability. Data protected by one instance of an application can only be unprotected by other replicas with the same machine key and it is different on other machines.

A suggested replacement of MachineKey is Microsoft.AspNetCore.DataProtection APIs which work for .NET Framework or .NET.
Scale.0003.label: MachineKey dependency is detected

links.title: Replace the ASP.NET machineKey in ASP.NET Core

Scale.0004.description:
Potential duplex communication is detected.

WebSockets work in most Azure environments and will not block migration. However, they need to be carefully reviewed to ensure the application will work correctly when it is scaled out.

Applications may require a communication backplane if broadcasting a message from one scaled out instance should also broadcast that message from other instances. Similarly, it may be necessary to enable session affinity if it’s required that users reconnect to the same server after a disconnect.

Similar issues could arise when server sent event streams are used (response content type "text/event-stream").
Scale.0004.label: Potential duplex communication is detected

Security.0001.description:
MD5/SHA1 usage detected. 

 Due to collision problems with MD5/SHA1, Microsoft recommends SHA256 or SHA512. 

 Consider using the SHA256 class or the SHA512 class instead of the MD5 class. Use MD5 only for compatibility with legacy applications and data.
Security.0001.label: MD5/SHA1 usage detected

Security.0004.description:
Explicit password-based credentials usage is detected.

Ensure that the dependencies accessed with the credentials and the authentication mechanism used will both work from the target Azure environment.

Also, consider replacing explicit credential usage with passwordless alternatives. When credentials are loaded from secure sources it might be OK, however it is considered the best practice for Azure applications to use password-less authentication (via managed identity for example) or to store secrets and passwords in Azure App Configuration or Azure KeyVault.
Security.0004.label: Explicit password-based credentials usage is detected

links.title: Use managed identities for Azure App Service

SMTP.0001.description: SMTP connections in your code might not work on Azure. Outbound email messages that are sent directly to external domains are made available only to certain subscription types. We recommend using authenticated SMTP relay services instead.
SMTP.0001.label: SMTP connections detected

links.title: Set up emails with Microsoft 365 or Office 365

Connection.0001.description:
Connection string detected. It may not be available when your app is migrated to Azure.

Review and ensure it works from Azure. If you are connecting to a database, you might need to migrate the database to Azure. There are multiple ways to do it:
    1. Migrate to Azure SQL Database for additional benefits (see the link below).
    2. Consider Azure SQL Managed Instance if you need features that are not available in Azure SQL Database and you don’t want to use a VM.
    3. Migrate your database servers directly to SQL Server on Azure VMs.

To assess database migration effort, you can use Azure Migrate tool, see the link below.
Connection.0001.label: Connection string is detected

links.title: Migrate SQL Server database to Azure

Database.0002.description:
SQL database connection detected.

Ensure the database is available/reachable on Azure.

If it is not, there are multiple ways you can move your data to Azure:
    1. Migrate to Azure SQL Database.
    2. Consider Azure SQL Managed Instance if you need features that are not available in Azure SQL Database and you don’t want to use a VM.
    3. Migrate your database servers directly to SQL Server on Azure VMs.

To assess database migration effort, you can use Azure Migrate tool, see the link below.
Database.0002.label: SQL database connection detected

links.title: Migrate SQL Server database to Azure

Security.0002.description:
Connection strings without configuration builders detected.  

 Keeping connection strings directly in the app is not the best practice and might introduce security risks, increased maintenance, scalability challenges or compliance standards (such as PCI DSS, GDPR, etc.). 

 Instead, it is recommended to use configuration builders to get secrets from secure sources in Azure environment.
Security.0002.label: Connection strings without configuration builders detected

Security.0003.description:
Hardcoded sensitive data detected. 

 Avoid placing sensitive data such as passwords, ids, tokens etc., directly in config files and code since it compromises the security of your application. 

 Use Azure App Configuration or Azure KeyVault to store secrets.
Security.0003.label: Hardcoded sensitive data detected
